[[File:horsne dibjars i.jpg|thumb|300px|Grooves in a fan-shaped pattern and with one crossing, Gotland, Sweden]] [[File:rone halor ii.jpg|thumb|300px| Grooves, the one at left at the edge of another one, Gotland, Sweden.]] [[File:haffinds iv cut.JPG|thumb|300px|Cut of a groove measured in a groove on Gotland.]] [[File:Oja strands i.jpg|thumb|300px|A stone with grooves that has been put in the border of a prehistoric grave. The grooves are on the side of the stone. Gotland]] [[File:Grooves on Gotland.JPG|thumb|Grooves on Gotland]] [[File:Gantofta1.jpg|thumb|Grooves in Gantofta, Scania]] [[File:Gantofta2.jpg|thumb|Detail of the grooves in Gantofta]] There are '''grooves''' ({{lang-sv|sliprännor}}, {{lang|sv|slipskåror}}. Sw-En translation: ''sharpening grooves'') carved into rock in many places in Europe, and some of them appear on the [[Baltic Sea]] island of [[Gotland]]. They are common in France, where they were used to polish [[stone axe]]s.
In Sweden, there are also grooves in north-western [[Scania]] and [[Halland]]. In [[Gantofta]] located {{convert|14|km|mi|abbr=on}} south of [[Helsingborg]] a face of sandstone rock is engraved with thousands of grooves. Local tradition says they were made as [[Sharpening stone|whetstones]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://fornvannen.se/pdf/1930talet/1936_129.pdf|first=Torsten|last=Mårtensson|title=Sliprännornas praktiska bruk|journal=[[Fornvännen]]}}</ref>
Grooves in France date from the [[Neolithic]] and are called ''polissoirs''. Those in [[Aube|l’Aube]] date from c. 2500 to 2000 BCE. People who built [[dolmen]]s, erected [[menhir]]<nowiki/>s and made grooves supported an [[archaeological culture]] known as [[Seine-Oise-Marne culture|Seine-Oise-Marne]]. The l’Aube district had more than 130 monuments from this period including 49 grooves before 1927. Today there are only 34 including 16 grooves. Many stones were cut into roadstones or building blocks for homes.
Grooves have also been found in [[Tavastia (historical province)|Tavastia]] in Finland and in Luxembourg, as well as at [[Fyfield Down]] in England.
Neolithic Grooves have been found in Tamil Nadu, India.<ref>{{cite news |last=Subramanian |first=TS |date=21 July 2016 |title=Footprints of Neolithic age |url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/friday-review/Footprints-of-Neolithic-age/article14500973.ece|newspaper=The Hindu |location= |access-date=21 December 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Subramanian |first=TS |date=3 April 2013 |title=Bedrock on which Neolithic man sharpened stone tools found in T.N. |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/bedrock-on-which-neolithic-man-sharpened-stone-tools-found-in-tn/article4575216.ece|newspaper=The Hindu |location= |access-date=21 December 2016 }}</ref>
== Gotland == 3,600 grooves have been discovered on [[Gotland]],<ref name="register">{{cite web|last=Gannholm|first=Sören|trans-title=The Gotlandic grinding grooves – Stone age calendars?|url=http://stavar.stavgard.com/gotlslipsk/slipskaror.html|title=Gotlands slipskåror|publisher=Sören Gannholm|date=1993|isbn=91-630-1845-4}}</ref> of which 700 are in [[limestone]] outcrops, while the remainder are on c. 800 boulders and slabs. The grooves are {{convert|50|–|100|cm|in|abbr=on}} long, c. {{convert|10|cm|in|abbr=on}} deep and c. {{convert|10|cm|in|abbr=on}}wide.<ref name="HenrikssonAstro">{{Cite journal|journal=[[Fornvännen]]|author=Henriksson, Göran |title=Astronomisk tolkning av slipskåror på Gotland|year=1983|url=http://fornvannen.se/pdf/1980talet/1983_021.pdf|publisher=[[Royal Swedish Academy of Letters, History and Antiquities]]}}</ref>
The grooves began to attract scholarly attention in the 1850s. At first they were called "sharpening stones", but later they received the name "sword sharpening stones". After some time, newspapers and scholarly publications began to dispute this, since the shape of the grooves makes them unfit for sharpening swords. Another reason was that by 1933, more than 500 sites with grooves had been identified on Gotland. They were evenly distributed across the island. It was also noted that they ran in different directions and often crossed each other.
The dates and function of the grooves on Gotland have seen debate in recent decades between archaeologists who argue for a [[High Middle Ages|High Medieval date]] and some industrial function,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Swanström|first=Lennart|date=1995|title=Slipskåror och järnhantering på Gotland|journal=Gotländskt arkiv|issue=67|location=Visby|pages=11–18}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Lindström|first=Jonathan|date=1997|chapter=Fornlämningarnas orientering på Gotland: en kritisk granskning av den arkeoastronomiska tolkningen av slipskåror samt en studie av riktningsfördelningen hos öns forntida gravar, hus och medeltida kyrkor|title=Till Gunborg: arkeologiska samtal|publisher=Dept of Archaeology, [[Stockholm University]]|pages=497–508|editor1-first=Gunborg O.|editor1-last=Janzon|editor2-first=Agneta|editor2-last=Åkerlund|location=Stockholm|series=SAR : Stockholm archaeological reports, 1101-3087 ; 33|isbn=91-630-6053-1|id={{LIBRIS|7452427}}}}</ref> and proponents of an alternative theory who argue for a [[Neolithic]] date and a ritual calendar function. The latter support their view mainly with the idea that the direction of each groove might be given an astronomical interpretation, where each groove would mark a sightline towards a certain celestial phenomenon that may be reconstructed for a certain year during the [[Stone Age]].<ref name="HenrikssonAstro" /> The grooves under overhangs in Scania cannot have been used as sightlines in this suggested manner.
Certain late 1st-millennium [[picture stone]]s on Gotland carry grooves that have been made after the relief of the stones was carved, which show the grooves to be late. Likewise with the level above current sea surface of the lowest grooved outcrops on the island, that shows them to be no older than AD&nbsp;1000 judging from post-glacial shoreline displacement.<ref>{{cite book|last=Munthe|first=Henr|chapter=Om Gotlands s.k. Svärdslipningsstenar|title=YMER|date=1933|pages= H. 2–3|publisher=Svenska sällskapet för antropologi och geografi|location=Stockholm|id={{LIBRIS|8258525}}}}</ref> It has been suggested that on one picture stone, part of the Late [[Iron Age]] decoration is carved into the bottom of a groove, meaning that this groove must be older than the picture.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Henriksson|first=Göran|title=Nya undersökningar av bildstenen från Othemars i Othem|journal=Gotländskt Arkiv|date=1988|url=http://195.67.126.28/ga/arkiv/view.php?id=795}}</ref>{{failed verification|date=March 2012}}
